
Switching
🎯 Objective

Learn what switching is, how a network switch works, understand MAC address tables, switching methods, and why switches are essential in Local Area Networks (LANs).

📖 What is Switching?

Switching is the process of forwarding data frames between devices within the same Local Area Network (LAN).

A network switch receives a frame from one device and forwards it only to the intended destination device based on its MAC address.

Unlike a hub, which sends data to every connected device, a switch sends data only where it needs to go.

Why Do We Need a Switch?

Imagine an office with 50 computers connected together.

Without a switch (using a hub):

Every computer receives every frame.
More unnecessary traffic.
Lower performance.
Less secure communication.

With a switch:

Frames are forwarded only to the destination device.
Better performance.
Reduced network congestion.
Improved security.
How a Switch Works

Suppose:

PC1  →  MAC: AA:AA:AA
PC2  →  MAC: BB:BB:BB
PC3  →  MAC: CC:CC:CC

The switch builds a MAC Address Table:

MAC Address	Port
AA:AA:AA	Port 1
BB:BB:BB	Port 2
CC:CC:CC	Port 3

When PC1 sends data to PC3:

The switch reads the destination MAC address.
It checks the MAC Address Table.
It forwards the frame only to Port 3.

Switching Diagram
             +------------------+
             |      Switch      |
             +------------------+
             | Port1 | Port2 | Port3 |
                |        |        |
              PC1      PC2      PC3
          AA:AA:AA  BB:BB:BB  CC:CC:CC
If PC1 sends data to PC3, only Port 3 receives the frame.



MAC Address Table

A switch maintains a MAC Address Table (CAM Table).

It stores:

MAC Address
Switch Port
Entry Age

Example:

MAC Address         Port
AA:AA:AA            1
BB:BB:BB            2
CC:CC:CC            3

The switch learns these entries automatically by observing incoming frames.

Types of Switching
1. Store-and-Forward Switching
Receives the entire frame.
Checks for errors using the Frame Check Sequence (FCS).
Forwards only valid frames.

Advantages

High reliability
Error checking

Disadvantages

Slightly higher latency
2. Cut-Through Switching
Starts forwarding as soon as it reads the destination MAC address.
Lower latency.
Does not verify the entire frame before forwarding.
3. Fragment-Free Switching
Reads the first 64 bytes of a frame before forwarding.
Helps avoid forwarding collision fragments.

Switch vs Hub
| Feature                   | Switch       | Hub               |
| ------------------------- | ------------ | ----------------- |
| OSI Layer                 | Layer 2      | Layer 1           |
| Uses MAC Address          | Yes          | No                |
| Broadcasts to All Devices | No           | Yes               |
| Performance               | High         | Low               |
| Security                  | Better       | Poor              |
| Collision Domains         | One per Port | One Shared Domain |
| Intelligent Device        | Yes          | No                |


Switch vs Router
| Feature      | Switch                  | Router             |
| ------------ | ----------------------- | ------------------ |
| Works On     | Layer 2                 | Layer 3            |
| Uses         | MAC Address             | IP Address         |
| Connects     | Devices in the Same LAN | Different Networks |
| Main Purpose | Frame Forwarding        | Packet Routing     |


